                    >
                    Then multiply by the number of cylinders. Keep all
                    dimensions in the same unit (all inches or all millimeters).
                    The calculator does this automatically and converts the
                    result to CID, liters, and cc.
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md">
                  <button
                    type="button"
                    class="faq-question w-full text-left px-4 py-3 flex justify-between items-center"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium"
                      >What is the difference between cc, liters, and cubic
                      inches?</span
                    >
                    <span class="ml-2 text-gray-500">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="faq-answer px-4 pb-3 hidden text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    They are all volume units:
                    <ul class="list-disc ml-5 mt-1">
                      <li>1 liter = 1,000 cc</li>
                      <li>1 cubic inch ≈ 16.387 cc</li>
                      <li>1 liter ≈ 61.024 cubic inches</li>
                    </ul>
                    Modern cars are usually rated in liters, motorcycles and
                    small engines in cc, and classic American engines in cubic
                    inches (CID).
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md">
                  <button
                    type="button"
                    class="faq-question w-full text-left px-4 py-3 flex justify-between items-center"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium"
                      >Does engine displacement include the combustion chamber
                      volume?</span
                    >
                    <span class="ml-2 text-gray-500">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="faq-answer px-4 pb-3 hidden text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    No. Displacement only includes the swept volume from bottom
                    dead center (BDC) to top dead center (TDC). Combustion
                    chamber volume and piston dish/dome volume are part of the
                    clearance volume and are used to calculate compression
                    ratio, not displacement.
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md">
                  <button
                    type="button"
                    class="faq-question w-full text-left px-4 py-3 flex justify-between items-center"
